div.span: Git Flow is one of the most common workflows. It takes advantageof several branches, each with one purpose. Master is the production branch, Hotfix is the branch for fixes in production and it must be merged to master and develop, Develop branch contains some new features and finally, release contains all new features to be deployed to production. Features should never interact directly with master, only with develop. This workflow is useful for big projects, it's not the best idea for small projects because of it complexity, also, is harder to have ContinuousDelivery / ContinuousIntegration.

div.span: Forking Workflow is commonly used in Open-Source based codes. It takes advantageof git forks. There are not branches strategies as other workflows, instead, if a developer wants to contribute adding new features or fixing some bugs, the developer must create a fork of the main source code, and all the new code must be written in that new fork. Once the work is done, the contributor may ask for a Pull Request to the main repository.

font.span: GitHub flow is useful for small and simple projects, is friendly with CI/CD and is easy to read it's history. Everything in master branch is deployable, for adding new features or code fixes the developer must create a new branch from master, once all the commits with the new code are done, the developer have must request a Pull Request for its review, once the new code is tested it could be merged into master branch for production. div.span: GitLab flow is probably the most safe and complex workflow. This flow is useful for systems that need a production environment as safe and as stable as possible. Master branch is a stagging environment, this means, master is not deployable for production, only for debugging. The workflow behind master could be as similar as Git Flow, but over master there are other branches for testing and deploying to production, crossing through several Merge Requests, making all the process slower but safer.
Deployments are automatic, based on branches or tags, tags are set by the user, not by CI, a
lso, is easier to have CI/CD than others workflows and the git history will be cleaner.
